data.content:
The main problem is using `Assert.IsTrue` for everything — when tests fail, you only get `"Expected: True, Actual: False"` with no diagnostic context. MSTest has purpose-built APIs:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Gives "Expected: 3, Actual: 5" on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Built-in collection assertions
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Found inactive users in results");

    // Assert.IsNotNull gives clearer failure than Assert.IsTrue(x != null)
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user in results");
}
```

**Key MSTest collection tools:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer intent + message |
| Order-sensitive compare | `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` | Element-by-element |
| Order-insensitive compare | `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` | Same items, any order |
| Contains check | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, item)` | Shows missing item |
| All items match type | `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(list, typeof(T))` | Type checking |

**Rule of thumb:** if `Assert.IsTrue` fails, would the message tell you *what went wrong*? If not, there's probably a more specific assert to use.
